         b'  <span style="font-weight: bold;">PhD students<br>\n      <br>\n '
         b'     </span><small>I am currently looking for good quality PhD\n '
         b'     students. Funding is available for students of sufficiently hig'
         b'h quality. Areas of interest include:</small> <br>\n      <p>\n\nSe'
         b'cure Information Flow<br>\n<p>\n      </span><small>A lot effort i'
         b'n making software secure goes into a kind of fire-fighting, i.e. dis'
         b'covering and closing vulnerabilities in code. However, even if all v'
         b'ulnerabilities have been eliminated, code still may not be secure. I'
         b't may contain covert channels that allow attacks on confidentiality '
         b'of information, integrity of information, and the privacy and anonym'
         b'ity of the user. Such covert channels leaking information may be wit'
         b'hin the logic of the program or be so-called side channels such as m'
         b'easuring execution times or heat dissipation over different runs. Th'
         b'e challenge of constructing security critical code for contemporary '
         b'software is enormous. Semantics based program analysis and type syst'
         b'ems have a large role to play in guaranteeing end-to-end information'
         b' security for networked systems.</small>\n</p>\n<br>\n   Semantic A'
         b'nalysis of Found Code<br>\n<p>\n    <small>Found code is code that'
         b' the analyser did not write. It may be source code or binaries. The '
         b'task is to understand what it does and the (common) motivation is de'
         b'fence against malicious behaviours. Techniques include reverse engin'
         b'eering, program analysis, testing, and use of SMT solvers. There are'
         b' a whole range of problem domains in this area, for example malware '
         b'classification and techniques for combatting packing, encryption and'
         b' rewriting engines.</small>\n</p>\n<br>\n\nTesting Information Trans'
         b'formers<br>\n\n<p><small>The hypothesis for this research is that '
         b'the answers to some long standing questions in the theory of testing'
         b' programs can be found or at least improved by viewing programs as t'
         b'ransformers of information and using techniques from information the'
         b'ory and the measurement of information flow in programs to build an '
         b'information theoretic theory of testing which answers questions such'
         b' as the following. How do I select the test suite? When is it adequa'
         b'te? What does adequate mean in terms of information? How do I order '
         b'the tests? There is a security aspect to this research. An improveme'
         b'nt in testing generally will improve the fire fighting of vulnerabil'
         b'ities and exploits, particularly when harnessed with information abo'
         b'ut attack vector templates.</small>\n</p>\n     <p> \n      <br>\n  '
